hem has a curved, modern-looking facade with broad blue glass panels and white framing.\n\nThe view broadens further to a parking area in front of the curved building. Several cartoon cars drive through the foreground, including a red car, a green car, and a purple car. As the parking-lot scene fills the picture, a small Fotomat drive-thru booth comes into view in the foreground. It has a bright yellow roof with large dark blue letters spelling “FOTOMAT” across the front. The booth has blue window panels and sits amid simple green shrubs. Cars circulate around it, emphasizing that customers can pull up without leaving their vehicles.\n\nA red convertible stops at the Fotomat booth. Inside the booth, a smiling female-presenting attendant with large fluffy white hair wears a yellow shirt under a dark blue vest or jumper. She leans out of the service window toward the driver. The driver is an older-looking, light-haired man seated in the red convertible, facing the booth. The attendant reaches down with a yellow envelope or claim form, and the driver’s side of the car is close enough for the exchange to happen directly through the open car window.\n\nA close view shows the yellow Fotomat form being filled out. The top reads “FOTOMAT’S PICTURE PICKUP PROMISE” in bold blue letters. Beneath it is a line that says the pictures will be ready on a specified day, followed by small checkboxes labeled with days of the week. A hand holding a red pen places a large check mark in one of the weekday boxes. The form is attached to a larger yellow envelope with a perforated edge. The top portion is then torn away along the perforation, becoming a separate slip.\n\nThe driver in the red convertible holds the small yellow slip up in his hand and smiles, looking at it as though he now has a clear pickup promise. The Fotomat attendant is then shown closer at the booth window, still smiling and holding the larger yellow envelope on the counter. The car’s red door frame and steering wheel 